success.question_hint:
• An isosceles triangle has two base angles equal.
  • After finding the value of x, you can use the exterior angle of a triangle rule.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

The angles opposite the equal sides in an isosceles triangle are equal. The exterior angle of a triangle is equal to the sum of the interior opposite angles.

success.question_text: Which diagram shows the reflection of the shape in line l?
success.question_hint:
• Consider each vertex of the original and the image.
  • The image must be the same distance from the line of reflection as the original triangle.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Under a reflection, each point on the image must be the same distance from the line of reflection as the corresponding point in the object.

success.question_text: Which of the following has exactly two axes of symmetry?
success.question_hint:
• ‘Exactly 2 axes’ means the shape cannot have more than 2.
  • An axis of symmetry is like a fold line for the shape.

review_1.column_1_text:
Solution

The rhombus has exactly two axes of symmetry.

review_3.column_1_text:
The square has four axes of symmetry.

The isosceles triangle has one axis of symmetry.

The circle has an infinite number of axes of symmetry.

Tip

An axis of symmetry is a line about which a shape could be folded so that the two halves match exactly.

success.question_hint:
• Pretend to be at the top of the solid looking down.
  • Look at the number of cubes in each of the 3 columns.

stimulus_1.text: This solid is made from 10 identical blocks:

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Practise looking at objects from different perspectives.

success.question_text:
If the model was 60 cm long, how high was its mast?

Type the number in the box, not the unit of measurement, e.g. for 15 cm type 15.
success.question_hint:
• The length of the model is 60 cm but the actual length was 25 m (or 2500 cm).
  • Work out the scale and use it for the height.

stimulus_2.text: A scale model of a sailing boat was made. The real boat was 25 m long and its mast was 30 m high.

review_3.column_1_text:
25 m is represented by 60 cm.

5 m would be represented by 60 cm ÷ 5.

So 5 m would be represented by 12 cm.

30 m would be represented by 12 cm × 6.

So 30 m would be represented by 72 cm.

The mast on the model would be 72 cm high.

Tip

It is not always necessary to find the actual scale used to answer questions about scale drawings.

• You need to work out the interior angles of a square and a regular pentagon.
  • A pentagon has 5 sides and hence the angle sum is 3 × 180°.

success.question_hint:
• There are many ways a cone can be cut.
  • Consider horizontal and vertical cuts.

stimulus_1.text: Which cross-section could be produced by cutting a cone?

review_3.column_1_text:
A cut parallel to the top of this cone will produce a circle.

A cut perpendicular to the top of this cone will produce an isosceles triangle.

Both X and Y can be produced by cutting a cone.

Tip

A cross-section can be thought of as a slice of a solid.

success.question_hint:
• Imagine or draw sketches of the quadrilaterals.
  • Check the sides and angles of each sketch.

review_1.column_1_text:
Solution

A trapezium is a quadrilateral with one pair of opposite sides parallel. None of the sides of a trapezium need be equal.

review_3.column_1_text:
The incorrect statement is ‘The opposite sides of a trapezium must be equal.’

Tip

A trapezium is a quadrilateral with one pair of opposite sides parallel. A rhombus is a parallelogram with a pair of adjacent sides equal.

choice_1.label: The diagonals of a rectangle must be equal.

choice_2.label: The opposite sides of a trapezium must be equal.

choice_3.label: The adjacent sides of a rhombus must be equal.

choice_4.label: The opposite angles of a parallelogram must be equal.

success.question_text: On which street is Sean now travelling?
success.question_hint:
• Notice the direction that North is pointing on the map.
  • Pretend you are in the car with Sean making the right and left turns.

stimulus_1.text: Sean was travelling south-east on Main Street and turned right into Honeysuckle Parade. He then took the first street on the left.

review_3.column_1_text:
Sean is now travelling on Alison Street.

Tip

Make sure you can use compass directions as well as understand that left and right must be from the perspective of the object described.

success.question_text: Which shape could not be added to the above figure to make a square?
success.question_hint:
• In your mind move the red triangle onto each of the shapes in the options.
  • A square will be formed in three of the options.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

A square is a rectangle. A square is a rhombus. A square is a parallelogram.

success.question_hint:
• As the lines are parallel, consider the rule for alternate angles.
  • The reflex angle will measure more than 180°.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

When a pair of parallel lines is cut by a transversal, the alternate angles are equal, the corresponding angles are equal and the co-interior angles are supplementary (add to 180°).

success.question_text: In which diagram has the shape PQRS been translated 4 units to the left and 3 units up?
success.question_hint:
• Look at a specific vertex of the red rectangle, say P.
  • Move this vertex the specified translation.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Another name for a translation is a slide. Each point moves the same amount.

success.question_hint:
• An isosceles triangle has two angles equal.
  • The angle sum of a triangle is 180°.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

An isosceles triangle has two equal sides and two equal angles. The angles opposite the equal sides are equal.

success.question_text:
What is the value of x?

Type the number in the box, not the unit of measurement, e.g. for 2 cm type 2.
success.question_hint:
• Work out the missing angles in the triangles.
  • The triangles are similar and so matching sides are in the same ratio.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

Similar triangles have corresponding angles that are equal and corresponding sides that are in proportion.

success.question_hint:
• A square-based pyramid has a square face and four triangular faces.
  • Imagine the solid formed when two of the pyramids are glued together.

stimulus_1.text: The identical square bases of two pyramids have been stuck together.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

For any solid, the number of faces plus the number of vertices is always two more than the number of edges. This result is known as Euler’s rule.

success.question_hint:
• Count the number of sides.
  • Subtract 2 from this number and multiply by 180° to work out the angle sum of the shape.
